Here's the approach:

### 1. Define each theme as a `ResourceDictionary`

Create three XAML files (e.g., `LightTheme.xaml`, `DarkTheme.xaml`, `HighContrastTheme.xaml`):

```xml
<!-- Resources/Styles/LightTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
                    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#FFFFFF</Color>
    <Color x:Key="PrimaryText">#1A1A1A</Color>
    <Color x:Key="Accent">#0078D4</Color>
    <!-- ... -->
</ResourceDictionary>
```

Use the same keys in every theme file so swapping is seamless.

### 2. Create a theme service

```csharp
public static class ThemeService
{
    public static void ApplyTheme(string themeName)
    {
        var mergedDicts = Application.Current!.Resources.MergedDictionaries;

        // Remove the current theme (always the last one you added)
        var existing = mergedDicts.FirstOrDefault(d => d is IThemeDictionary);
        if (existing is not null)
            mergedDicts.Remove(existing);

        ResourceDictionary theme = themeName switch
        {
            "Dark"         => new DarkTheme(),
            "HighContrast" => new HighContrastTheme(),
            _              => new LightTheme(),
        };

        mergedDicts.Add(theme);

        // Persist the choice
        Preferences.Set("AppTheme", themeName);
    }
}
```

> **Tip:** Have each theme class implement a marker interface (`IThemeDictionary`) so you can find and remove it easily.

### 3. Apply on startup

In `App.xaml.cs`:

```csharp
public App()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    var saved = Preferences.Get("AppTheme", "Light");
    ThemeService.ApplyTheme(saved);
}
```

### 4. Reference theme colours with `DynamicResource`

This is the critical part — `StaticResource` won't update at runtime:

```xml
<ContentPage BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource PageBackground}">
    <Label TextColor="{DynamicResource PrimaryText}" Text="Hello" />
</ContentPage>
```

### 5. Settings page picker

```xml
<Picker x:Name="ThemePicker"
        ItemsSource="{Binding Themes}"
        SelectedItem="{Binding SelectedTheme}" />
```

```csharp
// In your ViewModel
partial class SettingsViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    public List<string> Themes { get; } = ["Light", "Dark", "HighContrast"];

    [ObservableProperty]
    string selectedTheme = Preferences.Get("AppTheme", "Light");

    partial void OnSelectedThemeChanged(string value)
        => ThemeService.ApplyTheme(value);
}
```

### Key points

| Concept | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| `DynamicResource` everywhere | Enables live swapping without restarting |
| Same `x:Key` across all themes | Makes themes interchangeable |
| `Preferences` for persistence | Remembers choice across launches |
| Swap via `MergedDictionaries` | Clean add/remove, no leftover values |
